        "biography": {
            "errors": [],
            "value": "I have been working for the Naval Medical Research Unit No. 6 in the Virology and Emerging Infectious Disease Department since 2011. I have been involved in multiple studies aiming to understand the epidemiology and transmission of diseases such as dengue, Mayaro, Venezuelan Equine Encephalitis, Zika and Guaroa viruses.  I currently serve as a research physician for a Global Emerging Infections Surveillance (GEIS) study performing febrile surveillance that covers 12 civilian and military clinics and hospitals in Iquitos, located in the Peruvian Amazon. I participated in the project \u201cImmune responses to arbovirus infection\u201d.  This project attempted to isolate human neutralizing antibodies against arboviruses and evaluate their effectiveness as passive prophylaxis or therapy using established laboratory animal models. \nMy early publications focused on understanding the epidemiology, transmission and clinical manifestations of arboviral disease. These publications document that arboviruses are a common cause of human febrile illness in the Peruvian Amazon. Importantly, arbovirus-associated disease was not restricted to DENV in most of the study sites.",
